In October 2007, Docomo and [[Mitsubishi Electric]] showcased a prototype [[mobile phone]] at the [[CEATEC]] trade show. The phone checked health by tracking body movement and measuring calories, and included a [[breathalyzer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5hhzZNK2Qh8nBS4H9Tt_lDecgBE9QD8S3IR880|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029053227/http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5hhzZNK2Qh8nBS4H9Tt_lDecgBE9QD8S3IR880|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 October 2007|title=The Associated Press: New Prototype Phone Gives Fitness Check|date=29 October 2007|access-date=27 March 2018}}</ref> On January 24, 2008, NTT Docomo announced a partnership with [[Google]], which allowed all models after the FOMA904i models to view [[YouTube]] videos.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://plusd.itmedia.co.jp/mobile/articles/0801/24/news066.html |title=ドコモとGoogleが提携──各種サービスのiモード対応などを推進 |access-date=2008-01-26 |publisher=ITMedia+D モバイル |language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://plusd.itmedia.co.jp/mobile/articles/0801/24/news104.html |title=YouTube、ドコモの904i／905iシリーズに対応 |access-date=2008-01-26 |publisher=ITMedia+D モバイル |language=ja}}</ref> In 2008, NTT Docomo became a founding member of the [[Symbian Foundation]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=Mobile leaders to unify the Symbian software platform and set the future of mobile free |url=http://press.nokia.com/2008/06/24/mobile-leaders-to-unify-the-symbian-software-platform-and-set-the-future-of-mobile-free/ |publisher=[[Nokia]] |date=24 June 2008 |access-date=2011-04-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325025959/http://press.nokia.com/2008/06/24/mobile-leaders-to-unify-the-symbian-software-platform-and-set-the-future-of-mobile-free/ |archive-date=25 March 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

In May 2017, Docomo launched [[5G]] trial networks at [[Aomi]], [[Odaiba]] (Tokyo Waterfront City) and the area around [[Tokyo Skytree]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nttdocomo.co.jp/english/corporate/technology/rd/docomo5g/index.html|title = Docomo 5G | About DOCOMO | NTT DOCOMO}}</ref> It commercially launched its 5G network on March 25, 2020, making it the first Japanese operator to do so,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/18/business/tech/ntt-docomo-5g-services-march-25/|title = Docomo to launch Japan 5G services March 25, pipping SoftBank to post|date = 18 March 2020}}</ref> and making Japan among the first country in the world to launch 5G.{{Citation needed|date=April 2023}}

In August 2021, Docomo and [[Airbus]] demonstrated a solar-powered [[Airbus Zephyr|Zephyr High Altitude Platform Station]] (HAPS) for use with [[5G]] and [[6G (network)|6G]] technology. The trial took place in the United States over 18 days, and involved flying in the [[stratosphere]] and transmitting data at various speeds up to a distance of 140 km. If successful, then Docomo and Airbus would be able to provide communication services to remote islands, mountainous areas, and to remote sea lanes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mingas |first=Melanie |url=https://www.capacitymedia.com/articles/3830131/from-stratosphere-to-smartphone-ntt-docomo-trials-solar-powered-haps |title=From stratosphere to smartphone NTT DOCOMO trials solar-powered HAPS |work=Capacity |publisher=Capacity Media |date=2021-11-15 |accessdate=2021-11-15 }}</ref>{{Update inline|date=April 2023}}

